{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_antelope_ver01/data/ca06001655/00543171670/1920092401/0728.xml":{"full_text":"to consumers means that this problem is of the\ngreatest importance. But it is not for the\nfarmers\u2019 benefit primarily that such a move\nment must quickly culminate in action. The\nconsumer feels that somewhere between the\nfarmer and himself, too much is taken for a\nservice of comparative insignificance in contrast\nwith that which the producer himself renders.\n4 6\nThe farmers apparently are not alone in\ndesiring cooperative action. The survey shows\nopposition to cooperative movements only in\nthe New England and Pacific coast districts.\nSentiment is divided in Ohio, Illionis, and the\nother North Central Western States, but favor\nable in the Middle Altantic, the South Central,\nand the Southern States.\n66\nPolitically, the replies indicate that it is too\nearly to tell what the outcome of the November\nelection will be. Three months ago, there was\na\nstronger Republican sentiment than there\nappears to be now.\nThe trend has been, and is,\nRepublican. What it will be in November\nthese gentlemen do not prophesy.\n66\nThe large outstanding fact developed by the\nFidelity and Deposit Company seems to be that\nthe greatest issue in the public mind is being\n4 6\nShall\u201d and \"Will.\nAmong the most common of errors in the use\nof English, and one of the most difficult to avoid,\nis the confusion of \u201cshall\u201d and\nwill.\nThe rule\n6 4\nis that in the first person, either singular or plural,\n6 6\nshall\u201d must be used to indicate a future action.\nFor example, say\nI shall go to church to\n6 6\nmorrow\u201d; \u201cwe shall met you there\u201d; do not\nsay,\nwill go,\nwill meet.\nBut if you desire\n6 6\n6 6\nto express determination use \u201cwill\u201d; for example,\n4 6\nI will go and nothing shall prevent me\u201d;\nwe\nwill be obeyed.\u201d\nIn the second and third person the usage in\nregard to \u201cshall\u201d and \u201cwill\u201d is exactly opposite\nto the usage in the first person. Then the verb\n6 6\nwill\u201d expresses the future and \u201cshall\nis used\nto denote determination.\nAn amusing case in the misuse of the words\nwill\nand \u201cshall\nis found in the story of the\nFrenchman who fell into a river and cried,\n6 6\nI\nwill drown, and no one shall rescue me\u2019\nThe rule in regard to \u201cshould\u201d and \u201cwould\nis the same as the governing the use of \u201cshall\nand\n4 i\nwill.\u201d\u2014Columbus Dispatch.\noverlooked by the campaigners\u2014the high cost of\nliving. I think this conclusion might well be\njustified, but the blame should not be cast upon\nthe producer, and certainly the farmer has not\nreceived his share of the wealth which he creates.\ni l\nThe cost of living and foreign relations seem\nto be the main issue. Taxation and industrial\nrelations also occupy a place in the general\npolitical thought. Least interest appears to be\nshown in the railroad policy of the present\nAdministration, radical movements, and prohibi\ntion.\n6 6\nIt is clear that the country is on a sound\neconomic basis, and there is generally a spirit\nof confidence in the future, regardless of the\noutcome of the election.\n4 6\nThe business outlook appears to be good in\nevery section.\nWholesalers and retailers view\nthe fall and winter optimistically. The retailer\nis finding that the consumer is looking forward\nwithout fear to the winter, and his purchases\nfrom the wholesaler are founded upon this\noptimism. From the simple toiler up through\nthe tradesman to the industry and the financier\nthere runs the connected feeling of confidence.\u201d\n\u2014Franklin K. Lane.\nSeven Elements in Unconscious Teaching.\n1. Self-control.\u2014We can not control others\nunless we possess ourselves.\n2. Good natured.\u2014At peace with ourselves in\nside, naturally seeing the bright instead of the\ndark side of things.\n3. Confidence in yourself.\u2014Not conceit\u2014feel\nthat you are equal to the requirements of the\noccasion.\nPatient, not fussy. If you have great\npatience you can do almost anything you will\nwant to do with your class.\n4. Sincerity.\u2014It is the key to unlock the door of\nconfidence. Never resort to any trick methods.\n5. Sympathy.\u2014Our pupils are hungry for it.\nTake in account their different envionments.\nEnter into their joys and sorrows.\n6. Cheerfulness and Amiability.\u2014Cheerful folks\nare popular. You can not teach well if you can\nnot please.\n7. Earnestness.\u2014Realize what a privilege the\nopportunity of teaching is; don\u2019t trifle with the\nclass. When the teacher has self-control, good\nnature, confidence in herself, is sincere, sympa\nthetic, cheerful, and earnest appearance, the class\nis ready to listen to her.\u2014Wyron C. Settler in\nThe Christian Reporter.","height":"17420","width":"12732"}}
